    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. Since the environmental benefits like cleaner air and less traffic are pretty well-documented, do people usually see the equity concerns as a valid reason to scrap the whole thing, or is it more about figuring out how to make it fairer?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The equity concerns are usually not a reason to scrap the concept entirely, but rather a mandate to design the system correctly. The core of the debate is how to implement the pricing structure to ensure it doesn't unfairly penalize essential workers or low-income residents. Solutions like exemptions, rebates, or dedicated transit improvements funded by the toll revenue are the practical ways to make congestion pricing a fair and politically viable policy.",
      "source": "target",
